    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-01-18T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-01-18T13:00:00-05:00" n="639"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d639">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A5/853: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Phillips</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-01-18T19:00:00+01:00"
                            >January 18, 1937—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 18—3:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>28. My 22, January 16, 1 p.m.<note n="9" xml:id="d639fn9">Not printed.</note> In
                    reply to the Naval Attaché’s request for confirmation that Italy had accepted a
                    limitation of 14 inches for guns to be placed on future capital ships, the
                    Ministry of Marine has stated in writing that this limitation applies only to
                    future construction and not to the two capital ships now building which will
                    have guns of 15 inches. A copy of the reply which gives further details will be
                    mailed by the first pouch.<note n="10" xml:id="d639fn10">Not found in Department
                        files.</note>
                </p>
                <p>In this connection the British Ambassador told me yesterday that although he had
                    received no pledges regarding Italy’s adherence to the naval treaty he was
                    satisfied in his own mind, in view of statements made to him by Ciano,<note
                        n="11" xml:id="d639fn11">Galeazzo Ciano di Cortellezo, Italian Minister for
                        Foreign Affairs.</note> that the only remaining obstacle to Italian
                    cooperation was the delay in French and British ratification.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
